                            <comment id="12886952" author="owen.omalley" created="Sat, 10 Jul 2010 00:03:35 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Allen,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Namenode&apos;s configuration defines the mapping from long names to short names. It defaults to:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;*@YOUR.DOMAIN -&amp;gt; *&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;With that mapping, someone coming in from another domain will fail, even with the cross-realm stuff set up.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;hdfs@BAD.DOMAIN fails....&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;At Yahoo, we have two domains and we have rules for exactly how they map, but they amount to:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;*@YGRID.YAHOO.COM -&amp;gt; *&lt;br/&gt;
*@CORP.YAHOO.COM -&amp;gt; *&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So those two realms work, but anything else will fail. Depending on the translation that operations defines, they &lt;b&gt;can&lt;/b&gt; make a cluster insecure. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;joe@CORP.YAHOO.COM -&amp;gt; root&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;would be really convenient for joe, but not secure. &lt;b&gt;grin&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
